A simple and greener approach was adopted for the preparation of CDs from potato pulp [46]. The morphology of CDs was visualized by atomic force microscopy (AFM) and transmission electron microscopy (TEM) (Fig. 1
                        ). It illustrates that the CDs were uniform in size and near spherical in shape with good dispersibility. Surface functional groups of CDs were characterized by FT-IR (Fig. 1b), which shows peaks at 3234 cm−1, 1721 cm−1 and 1639 cm−1 that correspond to the stretching vibrations of −OH, CO and sp2 CC bonds, respectively. The optical properties of CDs were examined by both UV − vis and fluorescence spectra. In UV − vis spectra, a shoulder at 245 nm and a strong absorption band at 310 nm correspond to n−π* transition of CO and π−π* transition of CC, respectively (Fig. 2
                        a). The excitation-dependent emission is an intrinsic property of CDs (Fig. 2b) [69]. The thorough screening of the excitation wavelength from 300 to 540 nm confirmed that the maximum emission intensity appears at 445 nm (λex =365 nm) (Fig. 2b) and this was fixed for the fluorimetric studies.

One of the significant features that proves the effectiveness of any detection system is its limit of detection (LOD). The performance of the CDs-MnO2 assembly as an analytical tool towards quantitative detection of hydrazine was evaluated under the optimized condition by plotting relative fluorescence intensities against the concentration of hydrazine at lower concentration range (Fig. 7
                        ). A good linear correlation (R2
                         = 0.99814) was observed even at the micromolar concentration range (0.15–1.5 μM), from which the limit of detection was calculated as 0.15 μM (4.8 ppb) as the lowest point of detection which equals to 3σ/k.

An investigation was done on different water samples pre-spiked with hydrazine for monitoring the contamination. Thus, water samples were collected from various water bodies and then impaled along with hydrazine (1 μM) in deionized water. The fluorescence responses of the solutions were recorded and the intensity at 445 nm was plotted onto the standard bar graph (Fig. 8
                        ). In general, all the real samples showed good recovery of hydrazine by the CDs-MnO2 assembly (Table 1
                        ). The river and field water showed > 100% of recovery signifying already prevailing hydrazine contamination. The little lower recovery in tap water may be because of the presence of some competing species.
